{Welcome to this course! With this course, I continue the coverage of the series on 1.e4 for White. This course features White's responses against the French Defence, and the Caro-Kann defence. The philosophy behind this course has been to provide objective testing and theoretically challenging ideas. Both of the systems I propose are one of the most challenging ways to deal with the systems mentioned above. As usual, I recommend unknown ideas, which can be practically challenging for the opponent.} 1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann defence.} (1... e6 {The French Defence. Against the French, I recommend the strategically ambitious 'Advanced' variation.} 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] White grabs as much space as they can in the center.} c5 {Black usually tries to undermine our center.} (3... b6 {sidelines like this are covered in the tenth chapter.}) 4. c3 {[%cal Gc3e5] we strengthen the center. There are many different ways for Black to deal with this position.} Nc6 {Black's main move in the position.} ({Another possibility is} 4... Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 {Black delays ...Nc6. This doesn't help them, as the typical} 6. Be2 Bb5 {doesn't work on account for} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 $5 {This is covered in the tenth chapter.}) 5. Nf3 Qb6 {Black's main response. Here, I recommend} ({the rare} 5... Nge7 {and some other sidelines are covered in the thirteenth chapter.}) ({An important direction is} 5... Bd7 6. Be2 f6 {Black challenges our center. I call this the 'Erigaisi' variation, as he is championing it at the top level. Here, I recommend} 7. O-O fxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 10. Re1 O-O-O {and the rare} 11. Nd2 $5 {Where White has great chances to obtain an advantage from the opening.}) 6. Be2 $5 {and after} cxd4 ({sidelines like} 6... Nh6 {are covered in the fourteenth chapter.}) 7. cxd4 Nh6 8. Bxh6 Qxb2 {White can play the rare but challenging} 9. Nc3 Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 Qa3 11. h4 $5 {where we can pose plenty of practical problems. This move is virtually a novelty, so the chances of your opponent going wrong are quite high.}) 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 $5 {Optically unpleasant, yet a challenging move. White strengthens the center and asks Black to make a decision. Our strategic claim in these positions is that we keep extra space in the center. This variation is extremely complicated strategically and hence, we keep great chances to catch our opponent off-guard.} dxe4 {Black's main move.} (3... Qc7 {[%cal Rd5e4,Ye7e5] Black avoids the potential queen trade and prepares ...dxe4-e5. Here, I recommend challenging the center with} 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 $5 {where we keep good chances to obtain an edge out of the opening. This is covered in the second chapter.}) ({Chapter 3 deals with} 3... g6 4. e5 Bg7 5. d4 {where Black needs to be extremely precise in order to equalize.}) ({In chapter 4, I cover the rare} 3... e6 {system. Here, I recommend the novel} 4. Be3 $5 Nd7 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd3d4] with good chances to get an easy game and an objective advantage.}) ({Agains the natural} 3... Bg4 {we can go for} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 $14 {Where White has a better version of the '2 knights' system. This is covered in the first chapter.}) 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 {we reach another important branching point.} Nf6 ({sidelines like} 5... Bg4 {and}) (5... Nd7 {are covered in the fifth chapter. White remains better here.}) 6. Nfd2 {[%cal Gf2f3] preparing f3. Black has 4 major choices here.} g5 {Black's main move. This is covered in the ninth chapter. Here, I recommend the challenging} ({Chapter 8 deals with the variations arising after} 6... h5 7. h4) ({Chapter 7 deals with} 6... g6 7. f3 Bh6 8. a4 $5) ({Chapter 6 deals with sidelines like} 6... Ng4 7. Ke1 e5 {where I recommend the rare} 8. a4 $5) 7. a4 h5 8. Nc3 h4 9. h3 Nh5 10. Nf3 f6 11. e5 $5 {with good chances to gain an objective advantage.} *

