1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 $5 {a very interesting system. We are content with the idea of the possible queen trade arising after 3...dxe4 4.dxe4 Qxd1 5.Kxd1. At first sight, it seems like the sequence has gone horribly wrong for White. The king cannot castle anymore, while the Queens have been chopped off. However, if we go deeper, we'll understand that it's far from the case. The king will escape to f1 or to c2, while White keeps extra space.} Bg4 $5 {[%cal Rg4f3,Re7e6,Yb8d7,Yg8f6,Rb1c3,Yc2c4] This is an extremely popular response against the '2 knights' variation. However, against our system with 3.d3, this move seems a bit ineffective. White maintains greater flexibility with regard to the c-pawn and the b1-knight.} ({the critical} 3... dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 {This is covered from chapter 5 onwards.}) 4. h3 Bh5 {the trickier choice.} (4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Ge6]} 6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] This may seem like the 2 knight defence, but White has the extra option of playing exd5 & c4 in certain positions.} Nd7 $5 {the more flexible choice.} (6... Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 (7... Nbd7 {transposes.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2][%cal Ge4e5,Gf2f4] clearing the path for the f-pawn and preparing e5-f4.} a5 $5 (9... c5 {Here's where we get the chance to play} 10. exd5 exd5 11. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg2d5,Gc3d5,Gc1g5] with an edge for White due to the weak pawn on d5.}) 10. e5 Nfd7 11. a4 Qc7 12. f4 $14 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gc2c3,Gb1d2,Gd2f3] White doesn't need to play Nc3 here. We may play c3-Nd2-Nf3. We may also expand with h4 on the Kingside.}) 7. Bg2 Ngf6 ({Another played option is} 7... g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8e7] preparing ...Bg7-Ne7.} 8. Qe2 Ne7 9. O-O Bg7 {[%cal Rg7g6,Rf8g7]} 10. h4 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh4h5] a very thematic motif against ...g6-Bg7 lines.} h6 (10... h5 {[%csl Rg5]} 11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gc2c3,Gf3g5,Yc1g5]}) 11. Nd2 O-O 12. a4 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gd2f3,Gc2c3,Ge4e5,Ga4a5] White keeps an easy game thanks to the pair of bishops.}) 8. O-O Bc5 {[%cal Rd3d4] The most active square for the bishop.} (8... Bd6 {[%cal Rb8h2,Rb1c3,Rd5d4] can be met with the thematic} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5]} O-O 10. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} e5 11. f5 $14 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gg3g4,Ya2a4,Ra7a5]}) (8... Be7 9. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge4e5]} e5 10. exd5 cxd5 11. c4) 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge4e5]} dxe4 10. dxe4 e5 11. Nd2 O-O 12. a4 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gc2c3,Gh3h4,Gg2h3] with an easy and obvious edge for White.}) 5. Qe2 $5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge2e4] overprotecting e4 in anticipation of ...Bg6.} e6 {The most played response.} ({the natural} 5... Nd7 {can be met with} 6. exd5 cxd5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Nc3 Ngf6 9. h4 $1 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] trying to take advantage of the poor positioning of the g6-bishop. After} (9. g5 $5 Nh5 10. Nxd5) 9... h5 (9... h6 10. Bh3 {[%cal Gg4g5]}) 10. g5 Ng4 11. Bg2 (11. Nxd5) 11... Rc8 12. O-O $14 {White keeps an edge.}) 6. g4 Bg6 7. Bg2 $5 {Black has two major responses here.} Nd7 {[%cal Rf3e5] preventing Ne5.} (7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Be7 (8... Nbd7 {transposes.}) ({the brutal} 8... Bb4 {doesn't work. After} 9. Bd2 Bxc3 (9... Nbd7 10. a3 Be7 11. e5 Ng8 12. Nh2 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Gg4][%cal Gf2f4]}) 10. Bxc3 dxe4 11. dxe4 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc3g7]} Bxe4 {even though they win material, after} 12. h4 O-O 13. h5 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Gg2][%cal Gg4g5,Yb8d7,Re1c1,Rd8a5,Ra5a2]}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Ne1 {[%cal Gf2f4] preparing f4.} dxe4 11. dxe4 e5 12. Nd3 O-O 13. h4 h6 14. Be3 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gf2f3] we keep a stable edge due to the extra space. The bishop on g6 is misplaced.}) 8. Nc3 Ngf6 (8... Bd6 9. exd5 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge2e8,Gc3d5]}) (8... Bb4 {This has been played several times. However, after} 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 dxe4 11. dxe4 h5 12. g5 $1 {[%cal Gf3h4] we keep an easy game.} h4 13. O-O Ne7 14. Qe3 Qc7 15. a4 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gf3e1,Ge1d3] White is able to generate a lot of activity.}) 9. O-O Bb4 10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] overprotecting e4.} dxe4 $5 (10... O-O 11. f4 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gg4,Rg6]}) (10... e5 11. exd5 $16) (10... d4 11. Nd1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} e5 12. c3 {[%cal Gd1e3]} Bd6 13. cxd4 exd4 14. f4 {[%csl Re4,Rf4,Rg4]}) 11. dxe4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Ge4e5]} e5 12. a3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Rb4c3,Yb2c3,Ya3a4,Yc1a3,Ga3f8]} Be7 13. Nc4 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Rg6][%cal Ga3a4,Gc1e3,Gf2f3] Black ends up with a bad bishop on g6. The d6-square is vulnerable too.} *

