{Welcome to the second chapter. In this chapter, we will one of three main moves on the third move for Black.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge7e5,Rd5e4,Yd3e4] Black avoids the Queen trade and prepares ...dxe4-e5. This is usually played by ambitious players who want to keep their Queens on the board. Nevertheless, this move weakens the d5-square. White can try to take advantage of this by challenging the center with} 4. exd5 $5 (4. Nc3 dxe4 5. dxe4 e5 {The main line seems like a promising direction too, but I prefer exd5 because of its simplicity.}) 4... cxd5 5. c4 $5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb1c3,Gd3c4] hoping to get a spatial edge.} Nf6 {Black's main move.} ({It was also possible to start with} 5... e6 6. Nc3 Bb4 {delaying ...Nf6. Nevertheless, our setup remains the same.} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. a3 $5 {hoping to win the bishop pair.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nge7 (10... Nf6 {can be met with} 11. Be2 Bg4 12. O-O $14 {[%csl Gc1,Ge2] White keeps a comfortable edge thanks to the bishop pair.}) 11. Be2 Ng6 12. Be3 O-O 13. O-O Bd7 14. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5] With an easy-to-play position and a risk-free edge for White.}) (5... dxc4 6. dxc4 Nf6 (6... e5 $6 {This move, while natural, worsens Black's position. Not only does the e5-pawn remain vulnerable, but White now has an outpost on d5 to attack on.} 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Nb5 $5 {[%csl Rc7,Re5] harrasing the Queen.} Qb6 (8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 9. Be3 Bb4+ 10. Ke2 $1 {keeping the active bishop on the board.} (10. Nd2 $5) 10... Bc5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qd6 $16 {[%csl Gd6,Re5][%cal Gb5c7]}) (6... Nc6 7. Nc3 e6 8. Bd3 Nf6 9. O-O $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gc1g5,Gd1e2,Ga1d1,Gf1e1] White will follow-up with the most natural moves. We keep an edge thanks to the activity of the pieces.}) 7. Nc3 a6 (7... e6 8. Bd3 Bb4 9. Qc2 $14) (7... Nc6 {The computer's top choice.} 8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Bg5 {developing in a very thematic way.} h6 (10... O-O 11. Qc2 Bd7 12. Rad1 a6 13. Qc1 $14 {[%cal Gg5f4]}) 11. Bh4 O-O 12. Qc2 a6 13. Rad1 Nh5 $5 {The only way to neutralize some pressure.} (13... Bd7 $6 14. Bg3 $16) 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 (14... Qxe7 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Rxd4 Nf6 17. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Gd4d8]}) 15. Rfe1 Nf4 16. Bf1 Bd7 17. Ne5 $14 {White keeps an unquestionable edge thanks to the extra activity.}) 8. g3 $5 {[%cal Gc1f4] a dual-purpose move. Not only do we prepare to bring our bishop out to the active diagonal (h1-a8) , but we also prepare Bf4 simultaneously.} Bg4 (8... g6 9. Bf4 $16) 9. Bg2 Qxc4 (9... Nbd7 10. O-O e6 11. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ga1c1]}) 10. Ne5 Qe6 11. Qa4+ Nbd7 12. f4 $16 {[%csl Re8] Black is struggling due to their king's position.}) 6. Nc3 e6 (6... dxc4 7. dxc4 {transposes.}) 7. g3 Bb4 (7... Nc6 8. Bg2 Bb4 {transposes.}) (7... a6 {[%cal Gc3b5,Ra6b5]} 8. Bg2 dxc4 $6 {this is too risky.} (8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4 $14) 9. O-O cxd3 (9... Bd6 10. dxc4 $14 {[%csl Rd6]}) (9... Be7 10. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) 10. Qxd3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ga1c1,Gf1d1]} Be7 11. Bf4 Qd8 12. Qe2 $14 {We'll follow up by bringing the rooks into the center.}) (7... dxc4 8. dxc4 Nc6 (8... Bb4 9. Qb3) 9. Bg2 $16) 8. Bg2 O-O {played in all the games.} (8... dxc4 $5 9. O-O cxd3 {The computer is able to make it work, but it barely holds.} (9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O (10... cxd3 11. Ba3 $16) 11. Bf4 {transposes.}) (9... O-O {transposes.}) 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Nd4 Bxc3 (11... O-O 12. Nxc6 Bxc3 13. bxc3 bxc6 {transposes.}) 12. bxc3 O-O (12... Bd7 13. Nb5 $16) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ba3 {decision time.} Rd8 {This works still, but Black needs to find an incredible resource after a couple of moves.} (14... Re8 $1 {willing sacrificing the exchange. This is the only 'clean' way to equalize.} 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxc6 Bd7 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. Rfd1 (18. Bc1 Bb5 $13) 18... Bb5 19. f3 Nd5 20. c4 Bxc4 21. Kf2 a6 22. Rac1 Bb5 23. Rc5 $11 {the d3-pawn compensates for the missing exchange.}) 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxc6 Ba6 (16... Bd7 $5 {This still works, but seems a bit unnatural.} 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. Rfd1 Bb5 19. c4 Bxc4 20. Rac1 Bb5 21. f3 $14) (16... Rb8 {trying to the save the exchange isn't effective.} 17. Be7 Rd5 18. Rfb1 Rb6 19. Bxd5 (19. Rxb6 axb6) 19... Nxd5 20. Bc5 $16) 17. Be7 $3 Rac8 (17... Ng4 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 19. Rab1 $14) 18. Bxd8 Rxc6 (18... Rxd8 19. Rfd1) 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rab1 Rxc3 21. Rfc1 Ra3 22. Rb2 Ra4 23. Rc3 Rd4 (23... Bc4 24. a3 $14) 24. Rd2 e5 25. f3 Bb5 26. Kf2 Kg7 27. Ke3 $14 {We keep good chances to convert this.}) (8... Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4 $16) (8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nc6 10. cxd5 $16) 9. O-O {suddenly, Black's life isn't easy anymore.} dxc4 $5 (9... Nc6 10. Bf4 Qe7 11. Qc1 $16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ga2a3,Gf1e1]}) (9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 $5 {The only real way to challenge White's domination.} (10... Nc6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. c4 $16 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2]}) 11. Bf4 Qc5 (11... Qa5 12. dxc4 {transposes.}) 12. dxc4 Qxc4 (12... Nc6 13. Bd6 $18) 13. Ne5 Qxc3 (13... Qa6 14. c4 Nbd7 15. Qd4 $14) 14. Rc1 Qa5 15. Rxc8 Rxc8 16. Bxb7 Na6 17. Qf3 $14) 10. Bf4 {White keeps clear pressure in these lines.} Qc5 (10... Qa5 11. dxc4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 $5 (12... Qxc3 13. Ne5 $18 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4,Gg2][%cal Gg2b7]}) 13. Bd6 Rc8 14. Nd4 Nc6 15. Nb3 Qa4 16. Qe2 $14) 11. Na4 Qb5 12. dxc4 Qxc4 13. a3 Be7 14. Nd4 {getting all pieces into the attack.} Nbd7 15. Rc1 Qa6 16. Nc3 e5 (16... Nc5 17. Ndb5) 17. Nf5 Bd8 18. Be3 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Rd8]} *

