1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7] Black prepares to get the bishop out to the active diagonal on g7. This bishop is usually neutralized by a pawn on d4, and hence, I recommend you to play} 4. e5 $5 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Gd3d4] preparing to neutralize the f8-bishop.} Bg7 (4... c5 {a speciality of Anton Guijarro. Black tries to prevent us from playing d4.} 5. c3 Nc6 ({While this may seem intuitive, after} 5... d4 6. Be2 Bg7 7. O-O Nc6 8. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4] Black is struggling due to space. The knight on g8 is in a spot of bother.}) 6. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4]} Bg7 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nh6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bb5 $16 {with a very easy position for White. We have more space; the knight on h6 is awkward, while the c8-bishop lacks a good square.}) (4... Bg4 5. d4 c5 $5 {this was tried in a few games. However, after} 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Nbd2 e6 8. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Re7,Rg7] Black has too many weaknesses on the Kingside.} Bxc5 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. c3 $16 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6]}) (4... f6 5. d4 Bg7 {transposes.}) 5. d4 f6 $5 {challenging our center. Black wants to get the knight on g8 in the game.} (5... c5 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bb5 Bg4 8. O-O e6 9. Nbd2 Nge7 10. h3 $16) (5... Bg4 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nc6 9. h3 $16 {[%cal Gd2f3] Black will have to give the bishop pair.}) 6. Be2 $5 {waiting for them to take on e5 so that our knight is centralized.} fxe5 (6... Nh6 7. exf6 exf6 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 Be6 10. b3 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rh6][%cal Gb1c3,Gf1e1,Gc1f4] with a risk-free strategic edge for White. We have more space, better pieces and less weaknesses.}) (6... Bf5 7. O-O Nd7 8. c4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rg8][%cal Gc4d5] With their king in the center, Black seems to be struggling a bit.} fxe5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d5]}) 7. Nxe5 Nh6 (7... Nd7 8. f4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gc2c3,Gb1d2,Ge1g1,Gd2f3] stablising the knight. We'll follow up with c3-Nd2-Ndf3 & 0-0.}) 8. Nd2 Nd7 9. f4 {the thematic plan in such positions.} c5 $5 (9... O-O 10. Ndf3 c5 11. c3 cxd4 12. cxd4 {transposes.}) (9... Nf5 10. Ndf3 $14) 10. c3 cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O (11... Nf5 $6 12. Ndf3 Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Qa4 $16) 12. Ndf3 Nf6 13. O-O Ne4 14. a4 $14 {White keeps an easier game thanks to the extra space in the center. We also keep chances to expand on the Queenside.} *

