{In the fourth chapter, we would cover the rare 3...e6!? and 3...Nf6.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 e6 {Strengthening the center. Black is hoping to get a KIA after Nbd2, or a French after 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.e5 Nfd7 6.d4. Instead, I recommend the fresh} (3... Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. d4 e6 {hoping to transpose to a French.} (5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Be3 Qb6 10. b3 $16) 6. c4 $5 {Not giving them the chance. White prepares Nc3-Bd3.} dxc4 $5 {While this changes the nature of the position, after} 7. Bxc4 Nb6 8. Bd3 c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O $16 {[%cal Gc1g5] White keeps easy play.}) (3... Nd7 4. e5 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Rd7][%cal Gd3d4,Gc2c3] we'll follow up with c3-d4 next.}) 4. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gb1d2] preparing Nbd2. This helps us keep the bishop on a more active square. There are virtually zero games here, so here's some analysis of moves I feel might be the most natural ones.} Nd7 (4... Nf6 {a very provocative response.} 5. e5 $5 Ng4 6. Bc1 {[%csl Re5] Black wants to target our pawn on e5. However, we can claim that the knight is misplaced.} c5 (6... f6 {can be met with the thematic} 7. d4 {[%cal Gh2h3] with h3 coming up next.} Nd7 (7... fxe5 8. h3 $14) 8. h3 Nh6 9. exf6 {correctly avoiding Bxh6.} (9. Bxh6 gxh6 $13 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e5]}) 9... Qxf6 10. Bg5 Qf7 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. c4 O-O 13. O-O Nf5 14. Nc3 h6 15. Be3 $14 {[%csl Rc8]}) 7. c3 {[%cal Gh2h3] We now get a 'French Advanced' with Black's knight being on g4.} Nc6 (7... d4 8. h3 Nh6 9. g3 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Rh6][%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8,Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Gc1h6]}) 8. d4 Qb6 (8... Bd7 9. Be2 f6 10. h3 Nh6 11. O-O $14 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6][%cal Gd4c5,Gc3c4]}) 9. a4 $5 {An extra option since Black's knight is on g4.} cxd4 {probably the most natural sequence.} (9... a6 10. Be2 $14 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge1g1,Gh2h3]}) 10. cxd4 Bb4+ (10... Be7 11. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb1c3,Gb5c6] we are happy to swap the knight off in such positions. We'll cover such structures in greater depth when we cover the 'french advanced' lines.}) 11. Nc3 a6 (11... O-O 12. h3 Nh6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Bb5 $16 {[%csl Rh6]}) 12. Bd3 Bd7 13. h3 Nxd4 (13... Nh6 14. O-O Nxd4 15. Be3 Bc5 16. a5 Qb4 17. Na2 Qxb2 18. Nxd4 Bxd4 19. Rb1 Qxa2 20. Bxd4 $16) 14. hxg4 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 d4 16. Bd2 dxc3 17. bxc3 Bc5 18. Be4 Bc6 19. Bxc6+ bxc6 (19... Qxc6 20. Qxc6+ bxc6 21. Ke2 O-O 22. g5 $16) 20. Ke2 $14) (4... dxe4 $5 5. dxe4 Nd7 6. Nbd2 Ngf6 7. h3 {White keeps more space and has developed his pieces on the right squares.} Qc7 8. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4b5]} Bc5 (8... e5 9. Bc4 Bc5 10. Qe2 $16) 9. Bxc5 Nxc5 10. Qe2 a5 11. Qe3 {White keeps a strategic edge thanks to the extra space.} b6 {[%cal Rc8a6] preparing to swap the bad-bishop off.} 12. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh3h4]} Ba6 (12... O-O 13. g5 Nh5 14. e5 Ba6 15. O-O-O $14) 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. O-O-O $16) 5. Nbd2 Ngf6 (5... Qc7 6. d4 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 9. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gd3,Gd4,Ge3,Gf3]}) (5... e5 $5 {One of the most critical move strategically. Black gains space in the center.} 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Ge4,Re5] challenging the center since we are better developed.} Ngf6 (6... exd4 7. Bxd4 $14) 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. dxe5 $5 Nxe3 9. fxe3 {[%csl Re3,Re5,Rf7][%cal Gf1c4,Ye5e6,Yf1d3] The pawns on e5/e3 might seem a bit weak, but Black's kingside is also quite soft.} Qa5 (9... Be7 10. Bd3 Nc5 11. Qe2 $14) (9... Qc7 10. Nc4 $16) 10. e6 $5 {Weakening the Kingside.} fxe6 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1] preparing to safeguard the king.} Nf6 (12... O-O $4 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qd3+) 13. a3 {Black is already struggling due to their c8-bishop.} Bd7 (13... O-O 14. O-O-O $16 {[%csl Rc8]}) 14. O-O-O Bc7 15. Nb3 Qh5 16. e4 $14) 6. e5 Ng4 7. Bf4 f6 8. exf6 {embracing the complications.} Qxf6 (8... Ngxf6 9. d4 $16) 9. Bg3 Qxb2 (9... e5 10. c4 $5 {[%csl Rd5] Black's central pawns are vulnerable.} Bd6 $6 (10... Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O $16 {[%csl Rd5,Re5][%cal Gd1b3,Gd2e4,Gc4d5] is also quite good for White.}) 11. Be2 O-O 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} Nb6 14. Ne4 $18) 10. d4 $5 {[%csl Rb2,Re6] locking the e6-pawn down and trying to trap the Queen.} e5 (10... Be7 11. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rb2] is quite dangerous for Black.}) 11. Rb1 Qxa2 12. Ng5 Nb6 13. Qf3 $1 Be7 14. Qf7+ Kd8 15. dxe5 $18 Bxg5 (15... Rf8 16. Qxg7 Qxc2 17. Bh4 $18) 16. Qxg7 Bxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Qxb1 18. Bh4+ *

