1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 $5 {The most critical move. Black forces a queen trade.} 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc2c3,Ga2a4,Ga4a6,Yf3e1,Ye1d3,Yf2f3,Gf1c4,Rc8e6,Yb1d2,Rf3d2] [#] An important strategic crossroad. Allow me to explain the important strategic details of the position. We have traded the Queens and have lost the privilege to castle. In return, White keeps extra space in the center. We plan to expand on the Queenside with a4-a5. Our king is usually on c2, but might land up on f1, especially when the f1-bishop is traded. Black should avoid trading the light-squared bishops. We can place our knight in the following ways: Nbd2-Nc4;Nfd2-Nc3-Bc4;Ne1-Nd3-Nd2-Nc4. Black would ideally like to gain space on the Kingside.} Bg4 $6 {This is quite natural, but weak. As mentioned earlier, Black should avoid the bishop trade.} (5... Nd7 {one of the most natural moves. Black develops their knight.} 6. a4 {We gain space on the Queenside. This is an important part of our strategy.} g6 (6... e5 {[%csl Re5] This move is usually bad in such positions. After} 7. a5 $1 Ngf6 8. Nfd2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gd2c4,Gc2c3,Gd1c2,Gb2b4] White keeps a risk-free edge.}) (6... Ngf6 7. Nfd2 Ng4 8. Ke1 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ga4a5,Gf2f3] we'll kick the knight away with Nb3-f3. We may then expand with a5 and continue to develop the pieces.}) (6... Nc5 {can be bet with the thematic} 7. Nfd2 {[%cal Gf2f3] preparing f3.} g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8h6]} (7... e5 8. f3 $14 {[%cal Gf1c4,Gb2b4,Gc2c3]}) 8. f3 Bg7 9. Ra3 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,Yb2b4,Yf1c4,Rc8e6] preparing b4. We want to play b4-Nc4 next. Note that ...Be6 will be met with Bc4.}) 7. a5 $1 Bg7 (7... Bh6 8. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd1c1]}) 8. Bc4 Ngf6 9. Re1 Nc5 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gb2b4,Yd1e2,Ye2f1] The king remains quite safe, while White keeps extra space.}) (5... g6 6. h3 {avoiding ...Bg4 ideas.} Bg7 7. a4 $1 {following the thematic plan of gaining space.} Nd7 8. a5 Ngf6 (8... Nc5 $5 9. e5 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh3g4] this is why h3 was important!} Bf5 {can be met with} (9... Nd7 10. Bf4 f6 11. exf6 Ngxf6 12. Bc4 $14 {[%csl Re7]}) 10. Bf4 O-O-O+ 11. Kc1 $14 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gb2b4,Gb1d2] White is better because of the extra space.}) 9. Nc3 Nc5 10. Bd3 Nxd3 11. cxd3 O-O 12. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gc3a4,Gg2g4,Gh1c1] with a very easy game for White. Continue to improve your pieces and expand.}) (5... f6 {[%cal Ge7e5] preparing ...e5. We don't mind this.} 6. Nbd2 e5 7. a4 $1 {continuing with the thematic plan.} Nh6 (7... Be6 $6 8. Bc4 $14) (7... Bc5 8. Ke1 Be6 $6 9. Bc4 $14) 8. Nb3 g6 9. a5 {expanding as usual.} Nf7 (9... Be6 10. Nfd2 Na6 11. Bc4 $14 {trade the light-squared bishops whenever you can!}) 10. Be3 Bh6 11. Bxh6 Nxh6 12. Nfd2 $14 {[%cal Gf1c4,Gc2c3,Gh2h4,Gd1c2,Gf2f3]}) 6. Be2 Nd7 (6... Nf6 7. Nfd2 Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 $14 {is quite similar.}) 7. Ne1 $1 {This move helps us trade our bad bishop for our opponent's good one.} Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 {[%csl Ge1,Ge2] Our king is now secured in the center. Black cannot attack it.} e5 $5 (8... Ngf6 9. f3 e6 10. a4 a5 11. Nd3 $16 {This is quite similar to the text.}) 9. Nd3 Ngf6 (9... f6 10. a4 Nc5 11. Nxc5 Bxc5 12. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ga4a5,Gc1e3,Gf2f3,Gg2g4,Gh2h4] White keeps the typical edge.}) 10. f3 Bd6 11. Be3 Ke7 12. a4 $16 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gb2b4,Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Ga4a5] White keeps the thematic spatial edge. We can expand on both flanks. Black' pieces are poorly placed.} *

