{Welcome to the sixth chapter. In the sixth chapter, we will begin covering the critical 5...Nf6 variation.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nf6 {The main move for Black. They develop their knight and hit the e4-pawn.} 6. Nfd2 {[%cal Gf2f3] the typical plan. We want to play f3-c3-a4-Nc4/Nb3 in some order next.} Ng4 $5 (6... e5 $6 {as usual, this move is weak.} 7. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3] following the thematic plans. Black doesn't have a great response.} Be6 (7... Bc5 8. Nc4 Nbd7 9. a4 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Gc4][%cal Gc2c3,Gb2b4,Ga4a5]}) (7... a5 8. Nc4 Nfd7 9. a4 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Rb6,Rb8,Gc4,Rc8,Rd6,Re5][%cal Gc1d2] this time, we may even play Bd2 to hit the a3-pawn. We can develop our pieces next and claim a strategic edge.}) 8. Bc4 Bxc4 9. Nxc4 $16 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ga2a4]}) (6... Nbd7 7. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Ga2a4] strengthening the center as usual.} e5 (7... h5 {This was tried in a couple of games. Black wants to play ...h4 & ...g5 next. We can play the simple} 8. h4 g6 9. a4 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3] and keep a stable strategic edge thanks to the extra space.}) 8. a4 {gaining space as usual.} Bc5 (8... a5 9. Nc4 $14) 9. a5 $16) ({the critical} 6... g5 {and}) (6... h5 {are covered in the subsequent chapters.}) 7. Ke1 e5 {The most played move. Black prepares ...Bc5.} ({Another interesting attempt by Black is to challenge the center with} 7... f5 {here, I recommend the thematic} 8. Nc3 e5 9. a4 $5 {gaining space on the Queenside.} Bc5 (9... Nf6 10. f3 $14) 10. exf5 Bxf5 (10... Nxf2 11. Nb3 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rf2][%cal Rc5b6,Ra4a5] wins material.}) 11. Nde4 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4,Re5][%cal Gf1d3] White remains better thanks to the weaknesses in the center.}) 8. a4 $5 {a rare, but an extremely interesting idea. We continue with our thematic plan without worrying about ...Bc5.} (8. Nb3 a5 9. a4 Be6 $15 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ge6b3,Gf8b4] This is what Black wanted.}) 8... Bc5 $5 {the critical test.} (8... Be6 9. Bc4 $14 {as usual, we are happy to trade bishops.}) (8... Be7 $6 9. a5 $14) 9. h3 $1 {the point behind our play.} Nxf2 $1 {the principled response.} (9... Nf6 10. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3,Yd2b3]}) 10. Rh2 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gg2g4,Gd2b3] This initiates a sequence of forced moves.} f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. g4 Bxc2 13. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 {In general, the material imbalance seems to be in White's favor. Black needs to be extremely precise in order to equalize.} Na6 $5 (14... O-O+ {can be met with} 15. Kg2 Nd7 16. Nc3 Nc5 17. Bc4+ Kh8 18. Nf3 {where they need to find} e4 19. Ng5 Bb3 $1 {the only clear way to equalise. However, after} 20. Be3 Bxc4 21. Bxc5 Rfe8 22. Ngxe4 {we still keep some chances.}) (14... Nd7 $6 15. Na3 $1 (15. Nc3 Nc5 $13) 15... O-O+ 16. Kg1 Bg6 17. Nac4 e4 18. Nb3 $14 {with a risk-free edge for White.}) 15. Nf3 $5 {The position might be fine objectively but Black would need to be accurate.} e4 (15... O-O 16. Bc4+ Kh8 17. Kg3 e4 18. Ne1 $14) (15... Nc5 16. Be3 Nxa4 17. Kg3 Nxb2 18. Nxe5 O-O 19. Nd2) 16. Ne1 Nb4 (16... Bb3 17. Be3 $16) 17. Kg3 Rf8 18. Bg2 $14 *

