1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nf6 6. Nfd2 {The point of deviation of the previous chapter. Black wants to play ...Bg7/Bh6 next. However, this doesn't challenge our spatial edge.} g6 7. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3] we strengthen the center as usual.} Bh6 $5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gh6c1] Black wants to trade their bad bishop. This has been played frequent by GM Aravindh Chithambaram.} (7... Bg7 {can be met with the typical} 8. a4 $1 O-O (8... h5 9. h4 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4g5]} O-O 10. c3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd1c2,Gd2c4] White keeps a spatial edge.}) 9. c3 {[%cal Gd1c2]} Ne8 $5 {played by Van Foreest.} (9... Rd8 10. Kc2 c5 {this was played in a couple of games.} 11. a5 Nc6 12. Nb3 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Ge4][%cal Gf1b5,Ga5b6] Black is struggling.}) 10. Kc2 Nd6 (10... f5 $6 {this can be tried too. Nevertheless, after} 11. Bc4+ Kh8 12. exf5 Bxf5+ 13. Bd3 $16 {White remains on top.}) 11. Nc4 f5 (11... Be6 12. Nba3 f5 13. e5 $16) 12. e5 $16 {Although Black won the game, White was significantly better placed in: 0-1 (41) Deac,B (2679) -Van Foreest,J (2702) Chess.com INT 2022}) (7... h5 {can be met with the thematic} 8. h4 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4g5] stopping ...h4/g5.} Bh6 9. a4 $14 {White keeps a spatial edge. We want to play Nb3/Nc4-c3 next. ...Be6 can be met with the typical Bc4.}) 8. a4 $5 {gaining space on the Queenside as usual.} Be6 {The most popular response.} (8... O-O 9. c3 $14 {[%cal Gb1a3,Gd1c2,Gd2c4,Gb2b4]}) 9. Bc4 $1 {The standard response.} Bxc4 10. Nxc4 Bxc1 11. Kxc1 Nbd7 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gh7h5]} (11... g5 {is a bit premature. After} 12. h4 $1 g4 13. e5 $14 {[%cal Gf3g4] Black loses a pawn.}) 12. h4 $5 {an interesting way to prevent Black's idea of ...g5-h5-h4.} (12. c3 g5 $5) 12... O-O-O 13. Nbd2 Nh5 14. c3 {White keeps an easy game thanks to the extra space. Black has no obvious way to improve. A possible is} Nf4 15. Rh2 Nc5 16. b4 Ncd3+ 17. Kc2 $14 *

