1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nf6 6. Nfd2 g5 $5 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] Black gains space on the Queenside and doesn't give us the time to block their play on the Kingside with h4.} 7. a4 $5 {We gain space on the Queenside nevertheless.} h5 {The most played move. Black continues to gain space.} (7... Rg8 {This was played by some players.} 8. Nc3 (8. a5 $5 {is also a decent idea.}) 8... Nbd7 9. a5 {thematic. We gain space on the Queenside.} Nc5 10. f3 Be6 {this is met with the thematic} 11. b4 Ncd7 12. Bc4 $14 {[%csl Re6] trading the bad-bishop. White keeps the thematic spatial edge.}) (7... a5 $6 8. f3 Be6 9. Bc4 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rg5]}) (7... Nbd7 8. Nc3 Nc5 (8... Ng4 9. Ke1 $14) (8... h5 {transposes.}) 9. f3 $14) (7... g4 8. Nc3 Bh6 (8... h5 {transposes.}) (8... Be6 9. Bc4 $14) 9. a5 {thematic.} Be6 10. Nb3 Bxc1 11. Nxc1 Nbd7 12. Kd2 O-O-O 13. Nd3 Bc4 14. Ke3 $14 {White keeps the thematic spatial edge.}) 8. Nc3 h4 {The main move. Black squeezes space.} (8... g4 9. a5 {gaining space as usual.} (9. h3 $5 {is also quite decent.}) 9... Bh6 (9... h4 10. h3 Bg7 11. Be2 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf2f4] we end up with the thematic extra space.}) 10. h3 {[%csl Rg4,Rh5] hitting theweak pawns.} Be6 11. hxg4 Nxg4 12. Ke1 Nd7 13. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Ga1c1] The pawn on h5 remains vulnerable.}) (8... Nbd7 9. Nc4 Bh6 (9... Rg8 10. h4 gxh4 11. Rxh4 $14 {[%csl Ge4,Gf2,Rh5]}) (9... g4 10. f4 $5 Nc5 11. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gc2d3]}) 10. a5 Nc5 (10... h4 {can be met with} 11. f3 $1 {[%cal Gc1e3]} g4 12. Bxh6 Rxh6 13. b4 Nf8 14. f4 $14 {with a clear edge for White.}) 11. f3 Be6 12. Be3 Ncd7 13. Nd2 Ne5 14. Ke1 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4]}) 9. h3 {Another critical moment. We stop ...g4. We want to isolate the h-pawn.} Nh5 $5 {the most critical move. Black prepares ...e5-Nf4. Here, it's important to squeeze them down with} (9... Nbd7 10. Nf3 g4 11. hxg4 Nxg4 12. Ke1 $14 {[%csl Rh4]}) (9... Bg7 10. a5 $1 {waiting for ...Nbd7.} (10. Nf3 g4 11. hxg4 Bxg4 $13 {[%cal Gh4h3]}) 10... Nbd7 (10... Nh5 11. Nf3 f6 12. e5 $16 {[%csl Rf6,Rg5,Rg7]}) 11. Nb3 Bh6 12. Be2 Ne5 13. Ke1 $14 {[%csl Rf5,Rg5,Rh6][%cal Gc1e3,Gb3d4]}) 10. Nf3 f6 11. e5 {[%csl Rf6,Rg5,Rh4] stopping ...e5.} Nd7 {Here, I recommend the novel} 12. exf6 $5 (12. a5 $5 {is also quite decent.}) 12... exf6 13. Bc4 {[%cal Gh1e1,Gd1e2] surprisingly, Black only has one way to equalise here.} a5 $1 {the only move that equalizes. Black stops our expansion.} (13... Nc5 {can be met with} 14. Re1+ Kd8 15. a5 {squeezing space on the Kingside. We prepare Be3-b4/Ke2-Kf1. Black is struggling.}) (13... Bc5 14. Ne4 $14) ({the natural} 13... Bb4 {can be met with} 14. a5 $1 Kf8 (14... Nc5 15. Be3 $16) (14... b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Re1+ $14) (14... Kd8 15. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Gh1e1,Gd1e2]}) 15. Be3 Kg7 16. Kc1 {[%csl Rc8,Rd6,Rd7][%cal Gh1d1,Gc3e4] Black is struggling with their development.}) 14. Re1+ Kd8 {this strange move holds.} ({Instead, after} 14... Be7 15. Ne4 Kf8 16. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5]} Ng7 17. Ke2 Nf5 18. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Rd6,Rd7,Rf6,Rg5][%cal Gd2c3,Ge2f1,Ga1d1] Black is under pressure.}) 15. Ne4 Kc7 (15... Nc5 $6 16. Be3 $1 {is also dangerous for Black.} Be6 (16... Nxe4 17. Bb6+ $18) 17. Bxe6 Nxe6 18. Nd4 Nef4 19. Bxf4 Nxf4 20. Nxf6 Be7 21. Ng4 $14) (15... b6 $2 16. Nd4 $16) 16. Be3 $5 {Black should be able to equalise here. Nevertheless, this is still a complicated game with all results being possible.} (16. Nd4 Nc5 $11) *

