1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] The Advanced variation. Strategically speaking, this is the most ambitious move. White gains space.} c5 {Black's strategic claim in such positions is that they can try to undermine our center.} ({This move is usually played against 3.Nc3, but has been tried in this position too. Black wants to trade their bad-bishop with ...Ba6.} 3... b6 4. h4 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gh4h5] Simple and strong. We want to gain space on the Kingside.} Ba6 5. Bxa6 Nxa6 6. h5 h6 7. c3 {[%csl Ra6,Ge5,Gh5][%cal Gd1a4] even though they have managed to trade their bad bishop, Black stands worse due to the enormous spatial deficit and the awkward positioning of the a6-knight. A possible variation is} Qd7 8. Ne2 c5 9. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2f3,Ge1f1,Gf1g1,Gh1h3,Rb2b4,Re8c8] we'll play Rh3-Nf3-Kf1 next. If Black castles long, we can try to open up the Queenside with b4.}) (3... Nc6 $6 4. Nf3 f6 (4... Nge7 {can be met with} 5. c3 Nf5 6. Bd3 f6 7. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf3e5]}) 5. c3 fxe5 (5... Bd7 6. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Gd3,Rh7]}) 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Ne7 8. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rg6,Rh7][%cal Gd1h5] Black has several light-squared weaknesses.}) (3... Bd7 4. c3 c5 5. Nf3 {transposes to 3...c5 4.c3 Bd7 lines.}) (3... Ne7 4. c3 b6 (4... c5 {transposes.}) 5. h4 {thematic against ...b6.} Qd7 6. h5 h6 7. Nf3 Ba6 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 9. Qe2 Nb8 10. Na3 c5 11. Kf1 Nbc6 12. Nc2 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gh1h3,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Gc1d2,Gb2b4] with the typical edge for White. We may open up the Queenside with b4 at some point.}) 4. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4] we strengthen our center.} Qb6 $5 {delaying ...Nc6.} ({Another interesting attempt is} 4... Ne7 5. Nf3 Nec6 $5 {preparing ...Nd7/b6-Ba6.} (5... Nbc6 6. Na3 {transposes to chapter 13.}) (5... Nf5 {can be met with} 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3,Ge5][%cal Ge1g1,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] This is our ideal structure. White keeps space. Usually, Black has ...f6 in such positions. Since it's not possible here, White keeps a typical spatial edge.}) 6. Bd3 {we bring the bishop out to the most active square.} b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} (6... Nd7 {can be met with} 7. O-O Be7 (7... Qb6 8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Bc2 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1e3]}) 8. Be3 $16 {[%csl Gd3,Ge3][%cal Gb1d2] We have managed to develop all pieces comfortably while keeping more space.}) 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2a6]} a5 8. h4 Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. h5 h6 11. a4 {[%csl Rb5] fixing the b5-outpost. White keeps a huge spatial edge. Something like} Qd7 {can be met with} 12. Kf1 cxd4 13. cxd4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gh1h3,Gh3g3]}) (4... cxd4 {doesn't change much. After} 5. cxd4 Nc6 6. Nf3 {we should transpose somewhere, say after} Nge7 7. Na3 {transposing to chapter 13.}) 5. Nf3 Bd7 $5 (5... cxd4 {This is usually not great as we get the c3-square for our knight.} 6. cxd4 Nc6 7. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gf3] The structure white desires.} Bd7 8. a3 Nge7 9. Na4 Qc7 10. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gb2b4,Gf1d3] with a risk-free edge for White.}) 6. Be2 {developingh normally.} Bb5 $2 (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb5 {This is a more solid attempt. Nevertheless, after} (7... Nh6 {tr.}) 8. Nc3 Bxe2 9. Nxe2 Ne7 10. O-O {White keeps an edge due to the extra space.} Nbc6 (10... Nec6 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gd2f4,Gf4g4]} 11. Nf4 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gh2h4,Gg1g2,Ya1b1,Yc1e3]}) 11. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nf5 12. b4 Be7 13. g4 Nh4 14. Nxh4 Bxh4 15. f4 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gf4f5,Gc1e3] We have an enormous spatial advantage.}) (6... Ne7 7. dxc5 $16) (6... Nc6 {transposes to chapter 11.}) 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {a very brutal attempt to gain space.} Bxf2+ (8... Bxe2 9. Qxe2 $16 {[%cal Rc5e7,Gc1e3,Gf3d4,Gb1d2]}) 9. Kf1 Bc6 10. a4 {[%csl Rf2] The bishop on f2 is about to get trapped!} a5 $5 (10... a6 11. Na3 $1 {[%cal Gb4b5]} Be3 (11... Ne7 {can be met with} 12. a5 Qa7 13. Qd2 Ng6 14. Bd3 {[%csl Rf2] with grave problems for Black.} (14. b5 $16) 14... Bh4 15. Nxh4 Nxh4 16. Qg5 Ng6 17. Be3 $16) 12. a5 Qa7 13. b5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Bxb5 15. Bxb5+ Kf8 16. Ke2 Bxc1 17. Qxc1 $16 {[%csl Rg8,Rh8] Black is significantly lagging in development.}) 11. Qd2 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ge2d3] looking to trap the bishop.} Nh6 (11... axb4 12. cxb4 Ne7 13. a5 Qa7 14. Na3 Nd7 (14... Nf5 15. Nb5 $18 {[%csl Rf2]}) 15. Bd1 $16) 12. Bd3 Ng4 13. Qg5 Be3 (13... Bg3 14. Ra2 $18) 14. Qxg4 Bxc1 15. Qxg7 Rf8 16. b5 $16 {White keeps a clear edge thanks to the enormous weaknesses in Black's camp.} *

