{In the eleventh chapter, we will cover the 'Erigaisi' variation & some other sidelines, arising after 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 Bd7 6.Be2 in the French Advanced variation.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 $5 {The fight revolves around the control of the center.} f6 $5 {The 'Erigaisi' variation. Black tries to undermine our center. Arjun has had great results with this line. He has beat some very strong players with this system like Nepo, Petrosyan & Moussard. Nevertheless, strategically speaking, White keeps an easier game.} (6... Qb6 {This move is quite popular too. Black attacks the d4-point.} 7. O-O {We develop normally.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Nge7 {This is the usual plan by Black.} 9. Nc3 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5d4]} 10. Na4 $5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Ga4c5] We kick the queen away and win a tempo.} Qa5 (10... Qc7 $6 11. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Ga4c5,Rg2g4]}) 11. Bd2 Qd8 12. Bc3 {strengthening d4.} b6 13. Bd3 Be7 14. a3 O-O 15. b4 Rc8 16. Re1 $14 {[%cal Ga4b2,Gd1d2] White keeps a risk-free edge.}) (6... Rc8 7. O-O h6 {[%cal Rf3g5] avoiding Ng5.} (7... a6 {this is the most player move. However, after} 8. Na3 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nge7 10. Nc2 Nf5 11. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gg1h1,Gg2g4,Ya1b1,Yb2b4] White keeps the thematic ideas. ...Be7 will be met with g4 Nh4 Nxh4 Bxh4 f4. We may also play Rb1-b4.}) (7... Qb6 $6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4 $16 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ga2a4]}) (7... Nge7 $6 8. dxc5 Ng6 9. b4 {[%csl Gb4,Gc5]} Be7 10. Be3 Ncxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. f4 $16) 8. Nbd2 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nge7 (9... Nb4 10. Ne1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b5] the knight will be kicked back sooner or later.} Ne7 11. Ndf3 Nf5 12. a3 Nc6 13. b4 $14) 10. Nb3 Nf5 11. Bd2 a5 12. a4 Bb4 13. Bc3 b6 14. Nc1 $14 {White keeps a risk-free edge.}) (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nge7 {transposes to the next chapter.}) (6... Qc7 7. O-O f6 {transposes.}) (6... Nh6 7. Bxh6 gxh6 8. O-O Qb6 9. Qd2 {transposes to chapter 14.}) 7. O-O fxe5 {The critical response.} (7... Qc7 $6 {this is premature.} 8. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4] strengthening e5.} Nge7 (8... O-O-O 9. Bg3 {[%cal Ge5f6]} f5 {[%csl Rd5,Rd7,Re6,Rf5]} 10. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 11. b4 Be7 12. Na3 $18 {[%cal Ga3b5,Ra7a6,Yd1c1,Rb4b5] Black is busted on the Queenside.}) 9. Bg3 Nf5 10. exf6 Nxg3 11. f7+ Kxf7 12. hxg3 $16 {[%csl Rf7] White's advantage is undisputable.}) (7... Qb6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4 $16 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gc3c4]} Be7 10. c4 $5 {[%csl Rd5,Re6,Re8,Rf6] With the king in center, Black is struggling.} Bxb4 (10... dxc4 11. Nbd2 $18 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 11. a3 Ba5 12. Be3 Qc7 13. cxd5 $16) (7... cxd4 {this is weaker.} 8. cxd4 fxe5 9. dxe5 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c8] White has a better version of early ...fxe5 lines.}) 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qc7 {the most common move. Black hits e5 and prepares ...0-0-0.} (9... Bc6 $5 10. Be3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Yb1d2,Gd1d2]}) (9... Ne7 10. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8,Gf1e1,Ge2h5]}) 10. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge2h5,Rc7e5] preventing ...Qxe5.} O-O-O (10... Ne7 11. c4 d4 12. Bd3 O-O-O 13. a3 Nc6 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Yf3g5,Yb2b4] a rare, but a strong move. White prepares Nf3-Ng5. We may also play b4.} Ne7 (11... Qxe5 {can be met with} 12. Nf3 Qc7 13. Ng5 Nh6 14. Bh5 g6 15. Nxe6 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rh5,Rh6][%cal Ge1e6,Ge6h6] where Black is struggling.}) (11... Nh6 12. Nf3 Nf7 {[%csl Re5]} 13. Bg5 $5 {looking to deflect the rook.} Re8 (13... Nxg5 14. Nxg5 Kb8 15. Nf7 Ba4 16. Qxa4 Qxf7 {Here, it's important to play} 17. c4 $1 {avoiding ...c4. After} Qf4 (17... d4 18. Rad1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd1d3,Ge2f3,Gd3b3]}) 18. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d8] Black is under pressure.}) 14. Be3 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bh5 $1 Bd6 (16... g6 17. Bd4 $16) 17. g3 {They have a couple of choices here.} Ref8 (17... Qf5 {can be met with} 18. b4 g6 19. Bg4 Qf6 20. h4 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5,Ge3,Gg4][%cal Gd1d2,Ge3g5,Gg4d7] we are pressing on both flanks.}) 18. b4 Qf6 19. bxc5 Be5 20. Bd4 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Re6] with a good positional grip.}) 12. Nf3 h6 $5 {preventing Ng5. However, White is now in time to play} (12... Nc6 {can be met with} 13. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8] looking to deflect the rook.} Be7 (13... Re8 14. Be3 Nxe5 {this transposes.}) 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. b4 $16) (12... Kb8 {Comp's top choice. However, after} 13. Ng5 Nf5 14. Bd3 g6 15. Rb1 $40 {[%cal Gb2b4,Yg5f7] we keep great attacking chances.} (15. Nf7 Ba4 $11)) (12... Nf5 $6 13. Bd3 g6 14. Bg5 Re8 15. b4 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rc8]}) 13. b4 $1 {opening up the Queenside. A possible line is} Nc6 14. Be3 cxb4 15. cxb4 Bxb4 16. Rf1 Qa5 (16... Bc3 17. Rc1 $14) 17. Rb1 Kb8 18. Qd3 $14 {we are down a pawn but the initiative is obvious.} *

