1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 Nge7 {Black remains flexible and doesn't commit to ...f6. The knight may jump on both f5 or g6.} 7. O-O {Black has three major options here.} Ng6 (7... Nf5 {This used to be popular but after} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gc3,Ge5][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2b3,Gf1e1,Yb2b4,Ya2a4] White gets the desired structure.} Nh4 (9... Nfe7 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gb3d4,Gc1e3,Ya2a4,Yb2b4] we'll follow up with Nbd4/a4-b4.}) (9... O-O 10. b4 Bb6 11. a4 $14 {[%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc3][%cal Gf1e1] White keeps extra space.}) 10. Nbd2 O-O (10... Ng6 {transposes.}) 11. Nxh4 Qxh4 12. Nf3 Qh5 13. Re1 {[%cal Gc1e3] We'll follow up with Be3 next. White keeps an edge thanks to the extra space.}) (7... cxd4 {perhaps the most solid weapon for Black. They avoid dxc5 tricks.} 8. cxd4 Nf5 ({This is the most popular move. However, after} 8... a6 9. Nc3 Nf5 10. Bg5 {White seems to keep an easy edge.} Be7 (10... Qb6 {can be met with} 11. Na4 Qa7 12. Be3 b5 13. Nc3 Be7 14. Bd3 Nxe3 15. fxe3 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge5][%cal Gd3h7] We don't mind the doubled e-pawns, as the d4-pawn is strengthened. White's pieces are aiming at the Kingside. We keep more space.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Rac1 {Developing normally.} (13. Rae1 $5 {1-0 (32) Carlsen,M (2839) -Haria,R (2522) Durres 2023}) 13... Rae8 (13... Rac8 {can be met with the thematic} 14. Bd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1a4,Yc3a4]} Nh4 15. Nxh4 Qxh4 16. f4 Qe7 17. a3 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gb2b4,Rf4f5] White maintains a spatial edge.}) 14. Bd1 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Rd1a4,Yc3a4]} f6 (14... Nh4 15. Nxh4 Qxh4 16. f4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]}) 15. g4 Nh6 16. exf6 Rxf6 17. g5 Rg6 18. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg6,Rh6] Black's pieces are stuck.}) (8... Qb6 9. Nc3 Nf5 10. Na4 $14 {tr.}) (8... Ng6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Rc1 f6 (11... Rc8 12. Bd3 $14) 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Na4 b6 14. Nc3 $14) 9. Nc3 Rc8 (9... Qb6 10. Na4 $14 {[%cal Ya2a3,Yb2b4]}) (9... Be7 10. Bd3 $16) (9... a6 $5 {transposes.}) 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. Na4 Qa5 12. Rc1 h6 13. Bd2 Qd8 14. Bc3 $14 {[%cal Ya4c5]}) 8. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4] covering the f4-square and preparing a potential expansion with h4.} Be7 (8... f6 $5 9. exf6 $1 Qxf6 (9... gxf6 10. c4 $5) 10. Na3 a6 11. Nc2 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bd6 13. Ne3 O-O 14. Ng4 Qf7 (14... Qe7 15. Be3) 15. Ng5 Qe8 16. f4 $14) (8... cxd4 9. cxd4 f6 $5 {A modified version of the main line.} 10. Be3 $5 {This time, we are happy to sacrifice the e5-pawn.} (10. exf6 Qxf6 11. Na3 {doesn't work this because of} Bd6 $5) 10... fxe5 (10... Be7 {While this is possible, after} 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Nb3 b6 14. Re1 {[%cal Ga1c1] We keep a stable edge.}) 11. Nxe5 Ngxe5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nc3 $5 {Bringing all pieces into the action.} (13. Bd4 Bd6 14. Bh5+ g6 15. f4 Nc6 16. Bxh8 Qb6+ 17. Kg2 O-O-O $13) 13... Nc6 ({another critical line is} 13... Be7 14. Bd4 Bf6 {Where more or less forced is} 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Qxd5 Qc7 18. Rfe1 O-O-O 19. Rac1 Bc6 20. Bg4+ Kb8 21. Qxe5 $14 {White keeps some chances thanks to the extra material.}) (13... Bd6 14. Nb5 $14) 14. Re1 Bb4 (14... Be7 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Qxd5 $16) 15. Bh5+ g6 16. Bh6 $5 {White keeps great attacking prospects.}) (8... Qb6 9. h4 $16 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5]}) 9. h4 $5 {[%csl Rg6] We want to exploit the awkward positioning of the knight.} cxd4 $5 (9... h6 10. Be3 cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Ge3,Gf3,Rh7][%cal Gc3a4,Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Gh4h5,Ge2d3,Ya1c1,Yd3b1,Yd1d3,Gd3h7]}) (9... h5 10. Na3 $16 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Ga3b5,Ga3c2,Gf3g5] on top of the regular weaknesses, we may also attack h5/g5 this time.}) 10. cxd4 O-O 11. Be3 $5 {a slightly more confusing move order. We delay h5.} (11. h5 $5 {is also a decent option.}) 11... f6 12. h5 {Now's the time!} Nh8 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Nbd2 $5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ga1c1,Gf1e1] The point behind Be3. The d4-pawn is well-guarded. We claim that we keep a better position thanks to the superior pawn structure. We'll follow up with Rc1 & Re1 next.} Nf7 15. Rc1 {[%cal Ge2d3,Gd2b3,Rb7b6,Yb3d2]} a5 $5 (15... Rc8 16. Nb3 {This is already pleasant, as after} b6 17. Ba6 Rb8 18. Bf4 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Gf4b8,Ga6b7,Yb8a8] Black loses material.}) 16. Nb3 b6 17. Nbd2 {We have provoked a couple of weaknesses in Black's camp.} Nd6 18. Bd3 {[%cal Gh5h6]} h6 19. Re1 Nf5 20. Bxf5 exf5 21. Ne5 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Bxe5 23. Nf3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1d5,Ge3b6] Black might equalise, but the position remains dangerous.} *

