{In the fourteenth chapter, we will begin covering our absolute main line, arising after 4...Nc6 5.Nf3 Qb6!?. This chapter deals with the sidelines arising after 6.Be2, while the next chapter covers the main line.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 {[%csl Rd4] Black increases the tension in the center.} 6. Be2 $5 {We continue developing normally.} Nh6 $6 {This is quite popular. However, after} (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nge7 (7... Nh6 {this is covered in the next chapter.}) 8. Na3 {The thematic way to deal with ...Ne7.} Nf5 9. Nc2 Bd7 (9... Bb4+ {doesn't help. After} 10. Kf1 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gg2g3,Ya2a3,Yb2b4] we'll win a tempo by hitting the bishop with a3.}) 10. O-O Be7 11. Bd3 $16) (6... Bd7 {transposes to the previous chapters.}) (6... f6 7. O-O fxe5 8. dxe5 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gc3c4] We'll follow up with a3 & c4 next.}) 7. Bxh6 {White has a big advantage.} gxh6 (7... Qxb2 $2 {This is tempting. Black wants to grab the a1-rook. That being said, after} 8. Be3 $1 Qxa1 9. Qc2 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Ge1g1] Black's queen is trapped on the corner of the board.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 $1 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Ba3 $5 {the only to avoid losing the Queen. However, after} 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. O-O Qb2 15. Qa4+ b5 16. Qa6 $18 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ga6b7,Gb1a3] they lose material.}) 8. Qd2 {White remains strategically better due to the combination of having extra space and superior pawn structure.} Bg7 (8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Rg8 10. O-O $16) (8... Rg8 9. O-O $16) (8... Bd7 9. O-O Bg7 (9... Rg8 10. Na3 a6 11. Nc2 $18 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 10. Na3 O-O {transposes.}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c2,Gb2b4] preparing Nc2-b4.} Bd7 (10... cxd4 11. cxd4 f6 12. exf6 Rxf6 13. Nc2 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ga2a4]}) (10... f6 11. exf6 Rxf6 12. Nc2 Bd7 13. b4 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rh6][%cal Gc3b4,Gb4b5,Ga2a4,Gc3d4] Black has too many weaknesses in their camp.}) 11. Nc2 a5 (11... f6 12. exf6 Rxf6 13. b4 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4,Re6,Rh6]}) 12. Ne3 h5 13. Rad1 $14 {White remains better due to the better pawn structure.} *

