{In the final chapter, we will cover the main line of the 5...Qb6 system.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Be2 $5 cxd4 7. cxd4 Nh6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gh6f5,Yc6d4] Black doesn't let us play Na3 and prepares ...Nf5. It is important to give up some material here and play} 8. Bxh6 $1 Qxb2 (8... gxh6 9. Qd2 {transposes to the position covered in the previous chapter.}) 9. Nc3 $5 {a rare but extremely challenging move. The point is revealed after a couple of moves.} (9. Nbd2 gxh6 {The main line. This is also challenging, but the modern theory shows that Black should survive if they know their stuff here.}) 9... Qxc3+ (9... gxh6 10. Nb5 Qb4+ 11. Kf1 Qa5 12. Qc1 a6 13. Nd6+ $16 {[%csl Rf8,Rh6][%cal Gc1h6]}) (9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxa1+ 11. Bd1 gxh6 12. O-O $16 {[%cal Gd1a4,Gf1b1,Ra1b2] White remains on top. We have ideas of Ba4-Rb1 coming up next.}) (9... Bb4 10. O-O $18 {gives White a decisive advantage.}) 10. Bd2 Qa3 {Black's main response.} (10... Qb2 {This has been played by some players too. Black avoids the 11.h4!? idea. Nevertheless, after} 11. O-O {White keeps initiaitve. Black needs to be extremely precise in order to equalise.} a6 $5 {artificial, but strong. Black avoids Bb5.} (11... Nxd4 $4 {runs into} 12. Qa4+ Nc6 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. a3 $18 {[%cal Gf1b1]}) (11... h6 {can be met with} 12. Rb1 Qxa2 13. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Gb5,Gd2][%cal Gd1e2] White keeps initiative.}) (11... Be7 $6 12. Rb1 $16 Qxa2 $2 13. Bc3 $18) (11... Bd7 {This is what Anish gives against Nbd2 lines. However, in this case, after} 12. Rb1 Qxa2 13. Rxb7 Rb8 14. Qb1 Qxb1 15. Rfxb1 Rxb7 16. Rxb7 Be7 17. Bb5 $14 {White remains on top.}) (11... Qb6 {running away with the queen makes a lot of sense. However, after} 12. Rb1 Qd8 (12... Qc7 13. Qb3 Be7 14. h4 $14) 13. Qb3 Be7 14. Rfc1 O-O 15. Bd1 {[%cal Yd1c2,Yb3d3]} f6 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Qe3 $14 {We remain better.}) 12. h4 $5 Be7 13. Rb1 Qxa2 14. h5 h6 15. Re1 $44 {while this is objectively fine for Black, in a practical game, White is clearly pressing here.}) 11. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3a3] Not a novelty, but a very strong idea. White prepares Rh3. The computer throws a bunch of random moves for Black to equalise.} Be7 {The most natural move in my opinion.} (11... h6 12. Rh3 a6 $5 {this is the comp's suggestion. I don't think anyone can play in this fashion in a practical game. After} 13. Kf1 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gf3e1,Yh3g3,Gd2c3,Ya2a4,Ra3e7] We have a complicated middlegame on the board.}) (11... Bb4 {this probably feels like the other natural move that can happen in a game.} 12. O-O $1 {[%csl Re8]} (12. Rh3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Qa5 $15) 12... O-O (12... Bd7 13. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4]}) 13. Bc1 Qa5 14. Rb1 $16 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ge2d3] We keep great chances to build up initiative on the Kingside.}) (11... a6 $5 12. Rh3 Qe7 13. a4 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge1f1,Ga1b1,Gd1c1,Ge2d3]}) (11... Qe7 12. a4 $14) 12. Rh3 Bd7 {what else?} (12... O-O 13. Qc2 $18 {is already lost for Black!}) 13. Kf1 Rc8 (13... O-O-O 14. Ng5 $18) (13... h6 14. Rg3 Kf8 15. Ng5 $16) (13... Nd8 14. Qb1) 14. h5 {fixing g7.} (14. Rg3 $5) 14... h6 15. Rg3 Nb4 (15... Kf8 $4 {runs into} 16. Ne1 Qb2 17. Rb3 Qxd4 18. Nf3 Qe4 19. Rxb7 $18) 16. Ne1 {we keep an edge. Rg7 is up next.} *


